<span id="freeTextContainer7051765158852607258">I somehow missed this book and movie. The first publication was 1996, but I read the updated 2009 paperback from Broadway Paperbacks, NY. The author changed a few things after reader feedback and she lists the changes in the back of the book. As fan of historical fiction I do believe this is a first for me, and I liked it.<br/>Did I know about the 9th Century female pope? Nope. The author artfully constructs a believable heroic tale featuring a gifted girl in the Dark Ages and does not sugar coat her</span>
  <span id="freeText7051765158852607258" style="display:none">I somehow missed this book and movie. The first publication was 1996, but I read the updated 2009 paperback from Broadway Paperbacks, NY. The author changed a few things after reader feedback and she lists the changes in the back of the book. As fan of historical fiction I do believe this is a first for me, and I liked it.<br />Did I know about the 9th Century female pope? Nope. The author artfully constructs a believable heroic tale featuring a gifted girl in the Dark Ages and does not sugar coat her many challenges first at home, then schooling, then Rome.<br />Now that I have enjoyed this book I may try watching the movie but it may not satisfy.<br /><br />Library Loan (found next to Amanda Cross books I was flipping through)</span>
