  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_163997714" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/163997714" />
    <a title="Deb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5276322-deb"><img alt="Deb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526245087p2/5276322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/163997714?book_show_action=true">Apr 27, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deb" href="/user/show/5276322-deb">Deb</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer163997714" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9967953351288768490">This was absolutely everything you could want in a historical fiction. It is actually right up there with some of the best historical fictions I&apos;ve ever read. It was reminiscent of Follette at times, reminiscent of Rutherford at times, yet though I was reminded this book was thoroughly it&apos;s own. There was just so much to love and be entertained by. <br/><br/>Based on the real (although there is proof some believe legend) Pope John Angelicus aka Johanna aka Joan, like her namesake there is never a single d</span>
  <span id="freeText9967953351288768490" style="display:none">This was absolutely everything you could want in a historical fiction. It is actually right up there with some of the best historical fictions I've ever read. It was reminiscent of Follette at times, reminiscent of Rutherford at times, yet though I was reminded this book was thoroughly it's own. There was just so much to love and be entertained by. <br /><br />Based on the real (although there is proof some believe legend) Pope John Angelicus aka Johanna aka Joan, like her namesake there is never a single dull moment in this book.<br />We start with Joan's troubled childhood in Ingelheim and the twists, turns and surprises never stop until the last page of the book. We take a journey with Joan through the life of a woman who just wanted a chance at life and to be considered equal in the medieval world that she lived in. In a time when even learned men thought women to have small brains and to be evil "daughter's of Eve", Joan strove to persevere to her fullest potential in a male dominated world.<br />It's general knowledge that this is a book about a woman who must pose as a man in order to achieve her dreams but within the confines of this book the author explores so much more. The story is told from the view of various characters, Joan being the main and their experience in the world at this time and it's relation to Joan, shaping her and affecting her story as we follow her through life's journey. From Joan's parent's, her brothers and the people who doubt her it's also a show of how life shapes us by our early life experiences. The things we see and never forget challenge us in our future decisions to attempt to change the unavoidable past. <br />What I enjoyed most about this book, being a true romantic, was in the midst of all Joan's struggle for power and equality was a love story so contradictory to her very being and so pure and true. I loved watching it from it's onset, to it's declaration, to it's challenge, to it's duty, to death do them part.<br />The author researched these characters thoroughly as well as the lands and aesthetic of the time period. This is a historical lesson that just can't be missed. Not only do we get a view of the characters lives but the world and landscape they were woven into. View the middle ages in ways you may have never imagined. <br />This is a wonderful engrossing probably true story. It was an addictive page turner and I enjoyed every moment of it. I recommend this to everyone, actually because it is more than the historical fiction, there is romance, there is battle, there is religion, there is something for most lovers of "fiction" in general. I've given it 5 stars because that is the max but if allotted more I'd say 7 stars because it was perfect.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9967953351288768490" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


